74.words: Yeah, I think it's definitely this one just because having conversations about anything really in a small group, like one-on-one, I'm generally fine at, but a lot of times there will be some hot-button topic that affects a lot of people and then either an email chain starts popping or the group chat starts popping and people aren't really thinking about trying to... They just want to say what they want to say. They don't want to be understood. They don't want to really understand the other person. They just think, "Okay, I'm right. How am I going to get across that I'm right?" But they're not even thinking about how the other person will interpret it. It's just like, "What do I want to say? Okay, I will say that." There's just a lot of people sort of yelling what they want say without really any end goal in sight or any sort of collaborative process to get to some sort of decision. Because I do like debating a lot, but I don't like debating because I like just yelling at people. I like it because I like trying to understand where the other person's coming from and trying to get my point across in a way that makes sense to them and understanding how they will communicate and how I can get through to them, or being able to recognize when maybe I'm in the wrong or they have a good point, which is... I don't know, that's something I have worked a lot on and at this point pride myself on is being able to think actually not objectively, because I do still have some amount of bias, but I have worked a lot on being able to objectively think about what I'm saying and what I'm thinking of, whether or not I'm right or wrong, not that I do it perfectly, but I at least make the effort and I feel like that is what's important. And lot of times when it gets to this point, people are not making the effort anymore. And I guess miscommunication is coming just from it's just an important... It can be an important issue to people and to a lot of people. And then when you see the first rude text or email, then it's sort of like an invitation for you to do the same. And then I'll finish, it's just like the game's over, basically. No one's actually trying to work together anymore.
